        'title': 'Our Wheelhouse',
        'body': '<img src="https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/hphotos-xft1/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/11820570_917943998267180_1725558866_n.jpg" alt="Our Wheelhouse"><p>Basically, it‚Äôs a one bedroom with bunks cheap apartment on wheels. Our rig is a 2014 Fleetwood Bounder Classic 36H and her name is Mac. She‚Äôs 37.7 feet long, tows an Acme Tow Dolly, which our 2014 Fiat, Fifi, rides on. We have a Ford 6.8L Triton V10 gas engine.</p><p>Both the driver and co-pilot‚Äôs chairs swivel around to offer extra seating and open the space up to feel more home-like. All seats are made of faux leather. The couch and dinette both convert to sleeping areas; the couch open up to a full size bed with an air mattress topper, and the dinette table folds down to have a sleeping spot large enough for a child or two to sleep. we‚Äôve never used them for more than a family movie night or afternoon nap.</p><img src="https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/hphotos-xtp1/t51.2885-15/e35/12071140_900386743379039_228600832_n.jpg" alt="Interior"><p>In the kitchen, Justin has installed a new faucet arched enough to fill stock pots. We use an Ikea dish drying rack that scissors flat for easy storage. We use regular ceramic dinner plates and bowls, and when we‚Äôre driving, layer the ceramics with ShamWow TM towels to dampen the rattle. All of our cups and glasses are either heavy duty ceramic or plastic. Our fridge runs on a minimal amount of propane or electric, ideal for us when boondocking.</p><img src="https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/hphotos-xfp1/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/11910170_439922829526474_366932709_n.jpg" alt="Mollys Room"><p>Behind the living area is Molly‚Äôs bunkbeds and the half bath we have converted into a laundry room. Molly sleeps on the bottom bunk at night, and we use the top bunk to store her clothes, diapers, books, and have a changing station. Molly also keeps her stuffed animals on her bed, in addition to extra blankets for those cold nights! In the now laundry room (formerly ¬Ω bath), we have a 2100XC Splendide washer/dryer combo unit. It takes about 3-4 hours to wash a dry a really dirty load. We kept the toilet installed for those bathroom emergencies.</p><p>Next to Molly‚Äôs bedroom area is the Master Bedroom, where Anne and Justin sleep. We have a king size bed (in width but 6 inches short) with a 3‚Äù memory foam topper; the mattress from Fleetwood is just plain uncomfortable. There‚Äôs underbed storage, a wardrobe, 5 drawers, and overbed storage where we store almost all our clothes, sheets, and blankets. We also have a 27‚Äù TV that we‚Äôve hooked up our WiiU to play Mario Kart.</p><p>At the back of the RV is our main bathroom. Shower, toilet, and sink, being at the back we have a slightly-larger-than-usual-for-an-RV shower that we have installed a cut off valve on the shower head. Seeing as our hot water heater is 6 gallons, one of us easily runs out of hot water long before finishing a shower if it didn‚Äôt have a cutoff. Cold showers in the winter suck!</p><p>On our tow hitch, we have a dual receiver so we can carry bikes outside the RV while towing the car. We have an adjustable drop hitch to get the 5 1/4‚Äù drop we need for the ball hitch to receive the tow dolly. We use an Acme EZETOW dolly with surge disk brakes.</p><img src="https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/hphotos-xft1/t51.2885-15/e15/11350770_1443149529322453_100976224_n.jpg" alt="RV Exterior"><p>Under the RV we have tons of extra storage. We call this our basement, and in there you would find everything you would in a normal basement or garage. Toys, fishing gear, snow gear, Anne‚Äôs extra crafting stuff, extra board games, and so on. We also have access to our black/grey water tanks, shore power, generator, and propane tank in our basement area. We have pass-through storage in a few bays, making it useful to store extra long items like ladders and brooms.</p><p>Finally, what really gives our RV a spacious small home feeling are the three automatic powered slides in the living room and bedrooms. With them, we can go from about 100 square feet to about 250 square feet, really opening up the RV. Additionally, the electric awning just over the door and our outdoor rug give us a nice little lanai to take in those beautiful sunsets.</p><h2>Nitty Gritty Details</h2><ul><li>Length: 37‚Äô7‚Äù</li><li>Height: 12‚Äô</li><li>Width: 102‚Äù</li><li>Interior Height: 79‚Äù</li><li>Interior Width: 96‚Äù</li><li>Interior Storage: 134‚Äô (cubic feet)</li><li>Exterior Storage: 180‚Äô (cubic feet)</li><li>Grey Tank: 40 gal.</li><li>Black Tank: 30 gal.</li><li>Fresh Water Tank: 85 gal.</li><li>Propane Tank: 20 gal.</li><li>Water Heater: Tank 6 gal.</li><li class="spacer"></li><li>Engine: 6.8L Ford Triton V10</li><li>Transmission: 5 speed automatic w/overdrive</li><li>Torque: 457 lb-ft @ 3250 RPM</li><li>Horsepower: 362 Horsepower</li><li>Fuel Tank: 80 gal.</li><li>Wheelbase: 228"</li><li>GVWR: 22,000lbs</li><li>Front GAWR: 8,000lbs</li><li>Rear GAWR: 15,000lbs</li><li>GCWR: 26,000lbs</li><li>Hitch Rating Weight: 5,000lbs</li><li>Tongue Weight: 500lbs</li><li class="spacer"></li><li>Dual 11.0/13.5 Btu/h Ducted Air Conditioners</li><li>34,000 Btu/h Furnace</li><li>6-Gallon Quick-Recovery Water Heater w/Direct Spark Ignition</li><li>Battery Disconnect System</li><li>Halogen Lighting (partially upgraded compact fluorescents)</li><li>On-Demand Water Pump w/Filter</li><li>Livingroom 32" LED TV</li><li>Bedroom 27" LED TV</li><li>Dual Flat-Panel Monitors in Bunk Beds</li><li>King Bed</li><li class="spacer"></li><li>4-Point Automatic Levelers</li><li>5.5 kW EFI Onan¬Æ MicroQuiet Generator</li><li>50 Amp Service</li><li>Dual 6V Deep-Cycle 217 Amp Auxiliary Batteries</li><li>Exterior Wash Unit</li><li>Full Body Paint</li><li>Pass-Through Basement Storage w/Side-Swing Doors for Easy Access</li><li>Power Awning</li><li>Power/Heated Rear-View Mirrors</li><li>TV Antenna w/Signal Booster</li>'
