        'title': 'FAQs',
        'body': '<div class="question">What kind of engine do you have?</div><div class="answer">Gas powered 6.8L Ford Triton V10</div><div class="question">What do you tow with?</div><div class="answer">Acme EZE-TOW dolly pulls our 2014 Fiat 500L</div><div class="question">How‚Äôs towing the Fiat?</div><div class="answer">We hate it. It‚Äôs not designed for flat towing, so we had to get a tow dolly, which is just another set of headaches. We have yet to not be stressing about the tow dolly and car while we‚Äôre driving. It‚Äôs fallen off the dolly once, it‚Äôs hard to keep the current straps tight (we‚Äôre exploring alternatives), and someone (not naming names) drove the car up and over the dolly once too. </div><div class="question">What‚Äôs it like with a kid on the road?</div><div class="answer">It‚Äôs awesome! We love it, Molly loves it, it‚Äôs been an amazing decision! We‚Äôre showing her beautiful places across the country, meeting new people, and giving her a world education. Additionally, she gives us a good excuse to go to Walt Disney World (Anne‚Äôs never been)!</div><div class="question">Where does Molly sleep?</div><div class="answer">Molly sleeps on the lower bunk bed, every night. When we moved into the RV, we transitioned Molly from her crib to a ‚Äúbig kid bed‚Äù, and she has been sleeping in her bunk bed ever since. We store her clothes, books, and stuffed animals on the top bunk bed.</div><div class="question">Nice solar panel, does it run your whole RV?</div><div class="answer">While it keeps our batteries charged when we‚Äôre boondocking, we also try to conserve energy too. We only have 2 standard 6V deep cycle house batteries (~200 amp hours), so we can‚Äôt power that much. We use a Go Power 120 watt portable solar panel. </div><div class="question">How‚Äôs the internet?</div><div class="answer">It sucks! Wifi in RV parks is free, but usually beyond useless. We had an unlimited data plan from Omnilynx aka Verizon, but that program was closed down at the end of November 2015. We‚Äôve switched over to the new Karma unlimited data plan, Karma Neverstop, more on that here‚Ä¶ (insert link to karma information). We‚Äôre in the process of procuring another Verizon unlimited data plan from a friend or Ebay.</div><div class="question">How do you afford to RV full-time?</div><div class="answer">Justin picks up contract work as a webdesigner and we keep our costs down by watching our expenses. Anne is exploring options for remote working. We try to keep pay-to-park costs down by either boondocking a lot or getting out of season monthly rates at campgrounds.</div><div class="question">Are you homeschooling?</div>Well, Molly‚Äôs only 2, so not formally, but we are working daily on ABCs, 123s, colors, shapes, and geology (Molly really loves rocks!). We also aren‚Äôt planning on homeschooling at this time. Homeschooling is not something either of us foresee having the patience for. We plan to settle back down at an unknown location when it‚Äôs time for Molly to start kindergarten. That will be our next big adventure!<div class="question">How long do you plan to full-time?</div><div class="answer">Probably another 2-3 years, and then we‚Äôll be settling down for Molly to go to school. We‚Äôll keep the RV and still do a lot of traveling!</div><div class="question">What‚Äôs your favorite place you‚Äôve camped?</div><div class="answer">This is like asking, ‚Äúwho‚Äôs your favorite best friend?‚Äù, we‚Äôve camped in so many amazing places. And some not so amazing places, but our current favorite two places we‚Äôve camped are Emma Wood State Beach in Southern California, and the Bonneville Salt Flats in Utah.</div><div class="question">What made you choose to full-time RV?</div><div class="answer">Why not? We had always kicked around the idea of travelling the country in an RV when we retired. One day we actually looked at RV prices and realized we could do this now, before Molly started formal schooling. So we bit the bullet, got the financing, bought an RV, and hit the road. </div><div class="question">Why gas over diesel?</div><div class="answer">Gas RVs are cheaper, and there were more affordable options in gas RVs for us. We also wanted to buy new, not used.</div><div class="question">Gosh, don‚Äôt you find gas to be expensive?</div><div class="answer">Right now gas is fairly cheap. Additionally, we offset the price of gas by finding cheap or free camping, and by camping in one place for longer periods of time. Additionally, our solar panel helps us avoid running the generator as often.</div><div class="question">Do you use a carseat while you‚Äôre driving? Where does it go?</div><div class="answer">Yes, Molly rides in her carseat in the RV. We secure her carseat on the couch with a seat belt that is mounted to the steel frame. </div><div class="question">How does the üí©(poop) work?</div><div class="answer">We still use the factory installed toilets. Fun fact, marine and RV toilets use a flush lever on the bottom, which you push with your foot! Our main toilet is also a vacuum flush, and makes a lot of noise when it‚Äôs flushed, it sometimes frightens Molly. We‚Äôre still on the fence about getting a composting toilet for the amount of boondocking we do. </div><div class="question">Where do you put all your stuff?</div><div class="answer">Well, we downscaled enough for everything to fit in the RV. With some ongoing reorganization and purging we continue to make more room, and if we consolidated right, we could probably have an empty outside storage bay or two and a couple of empty storage cabinets inside. We try to put stuff we use occasionally in the outside storage, and our frequently used items inside. We also try to use digitized media as much as possible to save even more room. Our boardgame collection that we had a really hard time downsizing takes up the most room, between one storage bay and two inside cabinets.</div><div class="question">Where do you wash clothes?</div><div class="answer">We originally started out doing laundry in campground laundry rooms. It cost about $10 to run a week‚Äôs worth of laundry for a family of 3. After much begging, pleading, and grumbling by Anne, we bought an all-in-one washer/dryer and installed it in our half bath mid-coach. See more: (link to laundry room reno blog)</div><div class="question">Is your RV new?</div><div class="answer">Yes, we bought our RV new. Between renting many apartments and houses, owning a couple houses, buying both new and used cars, we decided that owning new would be what worked best for us. We got a great deal on our rig, as we bought it at the end of 2014, and it had been on the lot since 2013. The dealer was very eager to move it. </div><div class="question">How does it work in the winter?</div><div class="answer">Well, we haven‚Äôt done any serious winter camping yet. We try to choose places that stay above freezing, but do prefer cooler climates. When we do some winter/snow camping, we‚Äôll totally write a blog about it and share what we learned. In the meantime, these people have done some serious winter camping and have some winterizing tips: (list the wynns and maybe another site)</div>'
