          'type': 'blog',
          'title': 'The Plan- Financing!',
          'content': '<p>Since we want to be Fulltimers* it complicates things for getting a loan to buy an RV. I feel we are at the beginning of our journey into the world of getting a fulltimer RV loan due to the fact that banks are very reluctant to loan to people who can just move at will and easily disappear off the grid. Not that that is our plan! Because of the financially risky nature of fulltime RVers there are few lenders who will extend loans to individuals seeking to buy an RV to be their residence. Here is my experience trying to get an RV loan, where we went and what the process is like (this is not intended to be financial advice nor an endorsement for the loan providers mentioned below. I don‚Äôt receive any benefits from the following companies).</p><p>So when we first started looking for financing, it wasn‚Äôt as simple as getting a loan from one of our banks. Yes, we use multiple banks. All we kept reading about was Good Sam. They are apparently the number one name in Fulltimer RV and boat lending. They are also a part of Essex and Bank of the West. To apply for the loan with Good Sam (GS form here on out), you have to have an RV in mind that you‚Äôre going to purchase. We did our research and made a list of RVs that would work for us. When we applied for the loan we decided to put our top choice down, even though we were pretty sure it would be out of our range, because we thought, ‚Äúhey if they don‚Äôt approve us for $X amount, surely they‚Äôll tell us we can do something a bit lower‚Äù. We have high credit scores, great history, and Justin has a dependable high income. Apparently that wasn‚Äôt enough for GS. They also wanted recent comparable debt (like a mortgage) and thought our debt to income ratio would be too high after RV purchase (our monthly RV payments over 20 years would still be less than what we‚Äôre currently paying in rent in the Bay Area, but whatever). So they turned us down.</p><p>I went back to the drawing board to see if there was any other lender out there that wasn‚Äôt GS/Essex/Bank of the West. I found Alliant Credit Union, based out of Chicago, but with branches all over the US. We applied with them, they pre-approved us, it was a pretty easy process. For Fulltime RVers they want a bit of extra assurance you won‚Äôt bail on your loan payments, so they require a couple of extra contact (who aren‚Äôt on the loan), one years insurance premium to be held for 1 year, and 10-15% down on the loan. Not too bad! After being pre-approved for a reasonable amount, we found an RV within a couple of days, and hopefully we‚Äôll be able to pick her up within a week (see next post)!</p><p>So I guess thats the gist of how we financed our RV. The story comes out much easier than the whole process was, and it has felt pretty dramatic! Read on for more adventures!</p><p>*Fulltimers are people who use their RV as their primary, or sole, residence.</p>'
